physics. So I'll just touch base&nbsp;
very quickly with those things,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:12.120 --> 00:01:16.380
but I want you to appreciate that even though&nbsp;
we're doing very elementary things here, okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:16.380 --> 00:01:23.100
we are arriving at objects which are really very,&nbsp;
very fundamental for mathematics and physics.

00:01:23.100 --> 00:01:28.740
Okay, so before we get onto that though, let's&nbsp;
just enlarge our arithmetic a little bit and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:28.740 --> 00:01:34.860
introduce subtraction to our operations&nbsp;
that we're doing with these M sets.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:34.860 --> 00:01:41.880
So it's simple enough because we have a minus one&nbsp;
now. So we can define if A and B are M sets or&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:42.420 --> 00:01:50.400
anti-M sets, or maybe if we want to include both&nbsp;
of them at the same time, I might say A/M sets,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:50.400 --> 00:01:57.060
okay, to include the families of M sets and&nbsp;
anti-M sets and combinations of them. So then&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:57.060 --> 00:02:05.700
we'll define A minus B to be simply A plus one-bar&nbsp;
B, or in other words, A plus minus one times B.

00:02:05.700 --> 00:02:09.480
So here's an example. Here's an M set, perhaps A,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:09.480 --> 00:02:13.380
and here's another M set, perhaps B, and&nbsp;
we're taking the difference A minus B.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:14.880 --> 00:02:20.160
So this thing here, okay, um, minus this thing&nbsp;
here. The definition is that we should take the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:20.160 --> 00:02:25.980
same thing here and instead we should add minus&nbsp;
one, there's minus one times this second one.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:27.240 --> 00:02:33.840
Now in terms of a more standard notation, this&nbsp;
thing here, you see here, it has a 2 inside it,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:33.840 --> 00:02:39.720
has an empty M set that represents zero,&nbsp;
and this thing here is an anti-one, okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:39.720 --> 00:02:43.800
so that's what this thing is. And this thing&nbsp;
here, well, there's a two, there's another two,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:43.800 --> 00:02:54.420
so two, two. There's a one bar, okay, it's the&nbsp;
negation of one, and here is just an anti-zero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:54.420 --> 00:03:02.700
okay. So when we multiply the second one with the&nbsp;
minus one, what do we get? Okay, well, multiplying&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:02.700 --> 00:03:10.140
by minus one, what it does is it takes all of&nbsp;
the entries and it takes their antis. So that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:10.140 --> 00:03:16.740
means that all the bounding boxes have to change&nbsp;
color from black to red or from red to black. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:16.740 --> 00:03:22.500
this one here is going to change into a red box&nbsp;
with two black ones, same with this. This one here&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:22.500 --> 00:03:29.160
is going to change into a red box with a red box&nbsp;
inside. This one here is just going to change from&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:29.160 --> 00:03:35.340
an anti-zero to a zero, okay. And once we have&nbsp;
this, then the addition is of course just the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:35.340 --> 00:03:42.360
usual combining them. So we just put everything&nbsp;
in an M box, but when we do that, this thing here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:43.260 --> 00:03:51.180
this 2 and this anti-2 are going to annihilate&nbsp;
each other because these things are antis. They're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:51.180 --> 00:03:58.320
antis because the bounding box, the containers are&nbsp;
of different colors, one's black and one's red,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:58.320 --> 00:04:04.560
and otherwise inside they're identical. So they're&nbsp;
identical except that one's the anti of the other.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:04.560 --> 00:04:08.460
So they're going to annihilate. We'll still&nbsp;
have one more of them left over, we'll have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:08.460 --> 00:04:16.140
two empty boxes, and we'll have one of these and&nbsp;
one of these. And then when we list what we have,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:16.140 --> 00:04:27.720
we have one bar anti, so that's that thing there,&nbsp;
okay. And if it was black on the outside, that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:27.720 --> 00:04:34.380
would be a one bar, but it's red on the outside,&nbsp;
so it's a one bar anti. There's two zeros, there's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:34.380 --> 00:04:43.800
our anti-2, and this is an anti-one, okay. So&nbsp;
that's how we do subtraction in this M set world.

00:04:43.800 --> 00:04:47.100
Okay, so when we went from poly&nbsp;
numbers to integral poly numbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:47.100 --> 00:04:54.060
the big step was that we went from M sets&nbsp;
of natural numbers to M sets of integers.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:54.720 --> 00:05:04.260
And that means we have an interpretation now of&nbsp;
polynomials with also negative integer exponents,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:04.260 --> 00:05:09.600
not just natural number exponents. These are&nbsp;
integral poly numbers. And in this world,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:09.600 --> 00:05:15.780
there's this fundamental symmetry, the sigma&nbsp;
sort of reflection that takes Alpha to the N&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:15.780 --> 00:05:22.260
to Alpha to the minus N. And then with respect&nbsp;
to that, we defined an I poly to be symmetric&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:22.260 --> 00:05:30.120
if sigma of P equals P, and anti-symmetric or&nbsp;
alternating if sigma P equals minus P or P bar.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:30.840 --> 00:05:36.480
And I claim that the study of symmetric&nbsp;
and alternating integral poly numbers is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:37.020 --> 00:05:43.080
really something of a missing chapter of very&nbsp;
elementary algebra, something that you could&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:43.080 --> 00:05:51.000
have been taught back in early high school. But&nbsp;
because the emphasis there is strictly towards&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:59.460
the positive exponent side of things, polynomials,&nbsp;
this is not visible, okay. So we want to remedy&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:59.460 --> 00:06:06.720
that today, and we'll do that by starting with the&nbsp;
two important families of integral polynomials,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:06.720 --> 00:06:11.880
the A_Ns, which are going to be alternating, and&nbsp;
the B_Ns, which are going to be symmetric. And&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:11.880 --> 00:06:19.260
we're going to define them for arbitrary natural&nbsp;
numbers N, so for arbitrary integers N. So A sub N&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:19.260 --> 00:06:25.560
for any integer N and also B sub N for any integer&nbsp;
N. We could also restrict this to natural numbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:25.560 --> 00:06:31.200
but I think it's more convenient if we do this&nbsp;
in this sort of more natural generality, okay.

00:06:31.200 --> 00:06:35.640
So let's start with the symmetric ones.&nbsp;
We might call them symmetric binomials. B&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:35.640 --> 00:06:44.220
sub N is an integer. Here's the definition. B&nbsp;
sub N is the M set consisting of N and N bar.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:45.180 --> 00:06:54.000
So that's an integer and that's its negation. So&nbsp;
the N corresponds to Alpha to the N, and the N&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:54.000 --> 00:07:00.660
bar corresponds to what we might call Alpha to the&nbsp;
minus N. So we're taking this obviously symmetric&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:02.820 --> 00:07:10.260
integral poly number, okay. What do they look&nbsp;
like? Well, here's sort of a list near zero.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:10.260 --> 00:07:16.260
When N is zero, then both of these things are&nbsp;
zero. So we're getting zero, zero, in the,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:16.260 --> 00:07:25.440
that's the number two. It's important to make a&nbsp;
note of that, okay. B sub zero is two, not one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:25.440 --> 00:07:31.500
as you might otherwise think. And then B sub&nbsp;
one is going to be Alpha to the minus one plus&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:31.500 --> 00:07:37.740
Alpha. B sub two is Alpha to the minus two plus&nbsp;
Alpha squared, etc. And B to the minus one is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:37.740 --> 00:07:44.880
Alpha to the minus one plus Alpha to the minus&nbsp;
minus one. So it's Alpha to the minus one plus&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:44.880 --> 00:07:50.880
Alpha. It's the same as B sub one, okay. And&nbsp;
B sub minus two, I should put minus two there,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:52.200 --> 00:07:58.020
B sub minus two is Alpha to the minus two plus&nbsp;
Alpha squared. That's again the same as B sub two,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:58.980 --> 00:08:04.200
okay. So these are something of a basis&nbsp;
for the symmetric integral poly numbers.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:05.880 --> 00:08:11.220
And what's particularly interesting is what&nbsp;
happens when you multiply two of them. So let's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:11.220 --> 00:08:16.980
look at B3 times B5. There's B3, Alpha to the&nbsp;
minus three plus Alpha cubed. B5, Alpha to the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:16.980 --> 00:08:21.300
minus five plus Alpha to the five. And when we&nbsp;
multiply them, we get Alpha to the minus eight.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:22.920 --> 00:08:28.560
This combination here is Alpha to the minus two.&nbsp;
This combination here is Alpha to the two. And&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:28.560 --> 00:08:35.700
this combination is Alpha to the eight. And we&nbsp;
see that what we're picking up is a B2 and a B8,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:37.200 --> 00:08:43.020
okay. And note that the sum of three plus&nbsp;
five is eight and the difference here is two,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:44.340 --> 00:08:49.200
okay. If we squared one, so let's say take&nbsp;
B sub four and we square it. There it is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:49.200 --> 00:08:52.860
there. We square it. Well, we get the square&nbsp;
of the first term, which is Alpha to the minus&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:52.860 --> 00:08:56.880
eight. Square of the second term, which is&nbsp;
Alpha to the eight. And twice the product,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:56.880 --> 00:09:03.180
we get two. So that is then B zero.&nbsp;
There's B zero and Alpha to the eight&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:03.180 --> 00:09:10.020
plus Alpha to the minus eight is B eight. And&nbsp;
again, this zero is like the difference between&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:10.020 --> 00:09:13.920
the four and the four. And this eight&nbsp;
is like the sum of the four and four.

00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:22.740
So as we've already noted, B sub N is the M&nbsp;
set N bar N. Clearly, B sub N bar is equal to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:22.740 --> 00:09:29.760
B sub N because these two things just interchange&nbsp;
places. And the formula that we've just looked at,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:29.760 --> 00:09:37.320
a special case of, is that B sub M times B&nbsp;
sub N equals B sub M minus N plus B sub M&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:38.040 --> 00:09:43.440
plus N. And there's no restriction here on&nbsp;
the indices. They can be arbitrary integers.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:44.280 --> 00:09:48.780
A little bit more sophisticated is what happens&nbsp;
when you multiply three of them together, say B&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:48.780 --> 00:09:54.540
sub M, B sub N, B sub P. Then it's an exercise&nbsp;
for you to check that you're going to get four&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:54.540 --> 00:10:03.900
terms. You're going to get a B sub M minus N minus&nbsp;
P, B sub M plus N minus P, B sub M minus N plus P,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:03.900 --> 00:10:10.800
and B sub M plus N plus P. And remember that any&nbsp;
one of these things is unchanged if we negate&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:11.400 --> 00:10:20.400
the index. So for example, B nine times B four&nbsp;
times B three, nine minus four minus three is two,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:20.400 --> 00:10:28.200
nine plus four minus three is ten, nine minus&nbsp;
four plus three is eight, and nine plus four plus&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:28.200 --> 00:10:38.100
three is sixteen. And it also works when zero is&nbsp;
involved. So B seven, B four, B three, seven minus&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:38.100 --> 00:10:46.140
four minus three is zero. B seven plus&nbsp;
four, seven plus four minus three is eight,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:46.140 --> 00:10:53.520
seven minus four plus three is six, and seven plus&nbsp;
four plus three is fourteen. And do note that this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:53.520 --> 00:10:58.920
B zero being two is, you know, consistent,&nbsp;
sort of essential for these formulas to work.

00:10:59.460 --> 00:11:05.700
A little exercise for you, try to figure out&nbsp;
what the binomial expansion looks like in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:05.700 --> 00:11:11.400
this case. Just a variant of the usual one, but&nbsp;
it's worthwhile clarifying. So if we take B sub&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:11.400 --> 00:11:16.740
M for an arbitrary integer M and we raise&nbsp;
it to the K, where K is a natural number,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:16.740 --> 00:11:21.660
like zero, one, two, three, etc., what&nbsp;
do we get when we expand all of that out?

00:11:21.660 --> 00:11:25.200
So the B_N poly numbers were&nbsp;
pretty well the simplest symmetric&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:26.040 --> 00:11:32.460
integral poly numbers. Here are pretty well&nbsp;
the simplest alternating integral poly numbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:32.460 --> 00:11:38.280
the A sub Ns. So they're going to be defined also&nbsp;
for N, an integer. And they're defined in a very&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:38.280 --> 00:11:47.520
similar way. A sub N is the M set consisting of N&nbsp;
with anti-N bar, okay. And the anti has the effect&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:47.520 --> 00:11:55.440
of introducing a coefficient of -1. So we'll&nbsp;
write -Alpha to the minus N plus Alpha to the N.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:55.440 --> 00:12:05.040
And then we see that now if we negate the index&nbsp;
N, A sub N bar, we get the negation of A sub N.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:07.020 --> 00:12:12.660
And here are some examples. So A sub zero&nbsp;
is importantly zero, because when N is zero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:12.660 --> 00:12:19.740
there's a zero here and a zero anti, and the&nbsp;
zero and the zero anti annihilate, and we just&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:19.740 --> 00:12:27.420
get an empty set, or we just get zero. A sub one&nbsp;
is -Alpha to the minus one plus Alpha. A sub two&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:27.420 --> 00:12:33.660
is -Alpha to the minus two plus Alpha squared.&nbsp;
And A sub minus one is the negative of this one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:33.660 --> 00:12:39.780
so Alpha to the minus one minus Alpha. A&nbsp;
sub minus two is the negative of this one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:39.780 --> 00:12:43.800
so it's Alpha to the minus two&nbsp;
minus Alpha squared, and so on.

00:12:44.700 --> 00:12:51.660
So let's do a general multiplication. Let's&nbsp;
multiply A sub M times A sub N. So there's A&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:51.660 --> 00:12:58.440
sub M, there's A sub N. When we multiply, we get&nbsp;
four terms. So the product of these two is Alpha&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:58.440 --> 00:13:04.380
to the minus M plus N. The product of this one&nbsp;
and this one, or maybe this one and this one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:04.380 --> 00:13:11.820
is -Alpha to the M minus N. The product of these&nbsp;
two is -Alpha to the N minus M, and the product&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:11.820 --> 00:13:18.360
of these two is Alpha to the M plus N. And from&nbsp;
that, we can see that the product is actually,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:19.380 --> 00:13:28.080
well, this thing here, these two terms,&nbsp;
okay, are getting -B sub M minus N.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:28.800 --> 00:13:35.520
So we have to take these two out, and then we get&nbsp;
two plus signs, and we're getting B sub M minus N,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:35.520 --> 00:13:41.940
which is the same as B sub N minus M. And&nbsp;
these outside terms, both also with positive&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:41.940 --> 00:13:47.760
one coefficients, giving us B sub M plus N,&nbsp;
because here's Alpha to the M plus N and Alpha&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:47.760 --> 00:13:56.520
to the minus M plus N. So the product of these&nbsp;
two A's is a sum of two B's. And you might like&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:56.520 --> 00:14:03.600
to write down the corresponding formula for the&nbsp;
product of three of these A sub Ns, and also how&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:03.600 --> 00:14:11.700
do you take the corresponding binomial power of&nbsp;
a given A sub M, again K being a natural number.

00:14:12.720 --> 00:14:19.020
So it's not too hard to see that if you have&nbsp;
two symmetric integral poly numbers and you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:19.020 --> 00:14:23.220
multiply them, you're going to get another&nbsp;
symmetric one. If you have two alternating&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:23.220 --> 00:14:29.280
ones and you multiply them, you're going to&nbsp;
get a symmetric one. However, if you have an&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:29.280 --> 00:14:34.680
alternating one times a symmetric one, in that&nbsp;
case, you're going to get an alternating one.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:34.680 --> 00:14:40.860
So that's the formula that we're going to look at&nbsp;
now. What happens when we multiply an alternating&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:50.040
binomial with a symmetric binomial? A&nbsp;
sub M, there it is there, times B sub N,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:50.040 --> 00:14:56.580
there it is there. Well, just four terms, just&nbsp;
as before, we get a -Alpha to the minus M plus N,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:57.240 --> 00:15:07.140
we get an Alpha M, Alpha minus N, Alpha to the&nbsp;
M minus N, and these terms, Alpha to the N minus&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:07.140 --> 00:15:15.000
M with a minus sign, and a plus sign with Alpha&nbsp;
to the M plus N. And then these two terms here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:15.900 --> 00:15:21.240
these ones, Alpha to the M minus N&nbsp;
minus Alpha to the N minus M, that's A&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:21.840 --> 00:15:28.680
sub M minus N. And these&nbsp;
outside ones are A sub M plus N.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:29.820 --> 00:15:38.700
Now the A's, remember, are alternating. So if we&nbsp;
negate the index there, which we also could, then&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:38.700 --> 00:15:46.740
we'd have to put a minus sign, so we could also&nbsp;
write it as -A sub N minus M plus A sub N plus M.

00:15:48.060 --> 00:15:55.560
So this is a nice formula. And a very interesting&nbsp;
and important special case is when M is just one.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:56.340 --> 00:16:10.740
M is just one. In that case, you get A1 times&nbsp;
B N equals -A N minus one plus A N plus one.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:13.080 --> 00:16:19.920
And that then has the consequence with this little&nbsp;
formula here, which we might call a lemma, okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:19.920 --> 00:16:27.660
that if you have a chain of B's, B sub&nbsp;
K, B sub K plus two, B sub K plus four,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:27.660 --> 00:16:36.720
so going up by two each step, up to some B sub L,&nbsp;
so these are separated by an even number of steps,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:37.500 --> 00:16:47.100
then the result of multiplying by A1 is -A sub K&nbsp;
minus one, so one less than that index, plus A sub&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:47.100 --> 00:16:53.940
L plus one, one bigger than that index. And the&nbsp;
reason is, sort of immediate from this, because&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:53.940 --> 00:17:00.000
when you multiply the A1 times the BK, you're&nbsp;
getting a -A sub K minus one, that's that term&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:00.000 --> 00:17:08.640
there, plus a plus A sub K plus one. But that plus&nbsp;
A sub K plus one that you've just got is going&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:08.640 --> 00:17:14.640
to be canceled with the term that you're going to&nbsp;
get by multiplying the A1 times the B K plus two,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:14.640 --> 00:17:20.280
the left term. It's going to actually exactly&nbsp;
cancel that because you're going to get A sub K&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:21.120 --> 00:17:28.740
plus one and A sub K plus three, okay. So in&nbsp;
the intermediate spaces between these things,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:28.740 --> 00:17:33.720
the two A's that you're getting from the left&nbsp;
and from the right always have opposite signs,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:33.720 --> 00:17:39.180
and so they're going to cancel. And all&nbsp;
that's going to be left is the one to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:39.180 --> 00:17:42.000
the left of the left one and the&nbsp;
one to the right of the right one.

00:17:44.880 --> 00:17:52.620
Now, there's sort of two special cases of&nbsp;
this also. When K equals one, in this formula,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:52.620 --> 00:17:57.060
if we start with one and they go out by&nbsp;
two, so one, three, five, up to some L,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:57.060 --> 00:18:05.100
then the first term is going to be -A sub zero,&nbsp;
because one minus one is zero. And that's zero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:05.100 --> 00:18:11.700
so there'll only be one term, that's A sub L&nbsp;
plus one. On the other hand, if K equals two,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:11.700 --> 00:18:18.480
and we look at sort of even ones, if we start just&nbsp;
with B two, B four, B six, all the way up to B M,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:19.380 --> 00:18:28.200
then the formula is going to tell us what we&nbsp;
should get is -A sub one plus A sub M plus one.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:28.920 --> 00:18:34.800
But A sub one, okay, is... So&nbsp;
there'll be that on this side here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:34.800 --> 00:18:41.040
it's the same as over here. So we can bring it&nbsp;
to the left-hand side by putting an A one there,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:41.640 --> 00:18:47.040
okay. So if we rewrite the formula that you&nbsp;
get by starting with this one, with B sub two,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:47.040 --> 00:18:53.820
we rewrite it and bring the A sub one that&nbsp;
we get over here, then the result is just a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:53.820 --> 00:19:01.320
single A sub M plus one on the right-hand side.&nbsp;
So in both cases, if we have a string of B's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:02.280 --> 00:19:10.920
that are going up by two each time, and we&nbsp;
multiply by A one, we are getting a single A.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:12.300 --> 00:19:19.200
In fact, the A just has an index one bigger than&nbsp;
the biggest B that appears in each of these cases.

00:19:22.980 --> 00:19:30.960
That's a quite important kind of formula, which&nbsp;
motivates us to the definition of the objects&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:30.960 --> 00:19:37.680
that actually we're really interested in, which&nbsp;
are the central poly numbers, denoted by C sub N,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:38.400 --> 00:19:45.780
okay. So the central poly numbers, C sub N, and&nbsp;
now we'll stick with natural number indices, N&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:45.780 --> 00:19:56.580
equals zero, one, two, etc. So C sub zero is just&nbsp;
going to be one. C sub one is going to be Alpha&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:56.580 --> 00:20:03.420
to the minus one plus Alpha, so it's symmetric,&nbsp;
that's the same as B one. So there's a picture&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:03.420 --> 00:20:12.060
of C zero in terms of a mass distribution or a&nbsp;
density, single mass of unit size sitting above&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:12.060 --> 00:20:19.920
zero. Here's a picture of C one, unit masses above&nbsp;
one and minus one on our integral number line.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:20.760 --> 00:20:29.640
C two is going to be Alpha to the minus two plus&nbsp;
one plus Alpha squared, that's one plus B two. It&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:29.640 --> 00:20:37.440
has three equal masses, equally separated on the&nbsp;
number line, symmetric about zero at minus two,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:37.440 --> 00:20:44.400
at zero, at two. C three, similarly, Alpha to the&nbsp;
minus three plus Alpha to the minus one plus Alpha&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:44.400 --> 00:20:52.980
plus Alpha cubed, that's B one plus B three,&nbsp;
represented by four equally spaced unit masses,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:53.580 --> 00:21:00.300
symmetric around zero at minus three, minus one,&nbsp;
one, and three. And then we carry on like this.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:00.300 --> 00:21:08.820
C four is one plus B two plus B four, sort&nbsp;
of corresponding to the even powers of B,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:08.820 --> 00:21:14.280
except that's not B zero, okay. That's only half&nbsp;
of B zero, that's why I write it separately. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:14.280 --> 00:21:21.540
one plus B two plus B four. Well, the odd ones, B&nbsp;
one plus B three plus B four are like that. So we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:21.540 --> 00:21:27.180
just sort of follow that pattern for even and&nbsp;
for odd. So C four is Alpha to the minus four,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:27.180 --> 00:21:32.160
going up by steps of two all the way up to&nbsp;
Alpha to the four. C five, going from Alpha&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:32.160 --> 00:21:39.120
to the minus five to Alpha five, including all the&nbsp;
intermediate powers, which are separated from the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:39.120 --> 00:21:45.960
bottom by a multiple of two as we go up, minus&nbsp;
five, minus three, minus one, one, three, five.

00:21:48.420 --> 00:21:54.660
So these are the central polynomials. They're all&nbsp;
symmetric, okay. So you should think about them&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:54.660 --> 00:22:02.640
as being perhaps a somewhat more sophisticated or&nbsp;
a little bit more complicated variant to the B's.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:02.640 --> 00:22:10.980
They also form a basis of the symmetric poly&nbsp;
numbers. So if we have an arbitrary symmetric&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:10.980 --> 00:22:16.140
polynomial, we can write it uniquely in terms of&nbsp;
the B's. But it's not too hard to see we can also&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:16.140 --> 00:22:22.380
write it uniquely in terms of the C's. And the C's&nbsp;
are a little bit more sophisticated, but they're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:22.380 --> 00:22:29.640
also a little bit more uniform. And it turns&nbsp;
out that they're connected with a huge amount of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:30.600 --> 00:22:36.300
significant mathematics, okay. So very briefly&nbsp;
now, I just want to indicate very roughly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:37.140 --> 00:22:43.500
all the remarkable, or at least some of the&nbsp;
remarkable aspects to these central poly numbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:44.940 --> 00:22:48.960
C zero, C one, C two, C three, C four, etc., that&nbsp;
we've defined going on in this direction, okay.

00:22:51.360 --> 00:22:57.840
They're connected with so many important&nbsp;
aspects of 20th-century mathematics and physics.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:58.980 --> 00:23:04.020
Let's start here, okay. They're intimately&nbsp;
connected with Chebyshev polynomials,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:04.020 --> 00:23:08.340
which you will have run into, actually&nbsp;
Chebyshev polynomials of the second kind,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:08.340 --> 00:23:14.100
which you will have run into if you're a&nbsp;
member of my Wild Egg Mathematics courses&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:15.840 --> 00:23:22.320
YouTube channel, where I have a whole series on&nbsp;
interesting families of orthogonal polynomials&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:22.320 --> 00:23:27.780
and how to look at them in a somewhat novel&nbsp;
linear algebra/number theory point of view.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:29.340 --> 00:23:35.400
They're related to Gaussian binomial coefficients&nbsp;
and Q series, okay. And there's also, in fact,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:35.400 --> 00:23:40.020
over at Wild Egg, there's also a series of videos&nbsp;
that I'm doing on Q series, and the Gaussian&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:40.020 --> 00:23:45.600
binomial coefficients figure very prominently&nbsp;
there. So these are in some sense variants of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:45.600 --> 00:23:51.960
the Gaussian binomial coefficients, which are&nbsp;
in some cases more natural or maybe more useful&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:51.960 --> 00:23:58.140
than the Gaussian binomial coefficients, but not&nbsp;
in all cases. There's a good reason for studying&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:58.140 --> 00:24:03.720
both of them. And in fact, that other point&nbsp;
of view is closely related to quantum groups.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:03.720 --> 00:24:10.380
Also in physics, these things are coming out very&nbsp;
naturally in angular momentum quantum mechanics.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:10.380 --> 00:24:17.880
They figure prominently in representation&nbsp;
theory of Lie groups, okay. So in the world&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:17.880 --> 00:24:25.020
of Lie groups, there are things called compact&nbsp;
simple Lie groups, and the simplest one is SU2.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:25.020 --> 00:24:31.500
The simplest non-abelian one is SU2, okay, and&nbsp;
something called representation theory. And it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:31.500 --> 00:24:37.260
turns out that these things here are essentially&nbsp;
the characters, the irreducible characters of SU2&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:37.260 --> 00:24:43.800
when you view them in the right way. And as such,&nbsp;
they're also intimately connected with harmonic&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:43.800 --> 00:24:49.740
analysis on the three-dimensional sphere, not the&nbsp;
two-dimensional sphere that we find in our space,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:49.740 --> 00:24:55.980
but the three-dimensional sphere, which is another&nbsp;
manifestation of SU2. But you can do sort of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:55.980 --> 00:25:01.440
spherical harmonics on that thing, and it turns&nbsp;
out that these things are intimately connected&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:01.440 --> 00:25:08.520
with spherical harmonics on S3. They're very&nbsp;
close to the Weyl character formula, and arguably,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:08.520 --> 00:25:14.580
I've already shown you the Weyl character&nbsp;
formula today in the simplest of all cases, okay.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:15.540 --> 00:25:25.020
I actually also have to put in, yeah, I have&nbsp;
to put in another ADE graphs, okay. ADE graphs,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:27.060 --> 00:25:32.880
so the Weyl character formula applies to&nbsp;
all of these graphs. But in the AN case,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:32.880 --> 00:25:38.880
sort of a special case, this is actually the&nbsp;
simplest A case. It's the A1 case. So this is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:38.880 --> 00:25:45.960
like the simplest version of some huge story. And&nbsp;
there's also a series in my Wild Egg Mathematics&nbsp;&nbsp;

